In which case can java.util.Stream.peek() be skipped? Is it related to debugging?The Stream.peek() method is an intermediate operation that is used to "peek" at the elements of a stream before they are processed by the next operation. The method takes a Consumer function as an argument, which is used to perform some action on each element of the stream as it is processed.In terms of optimization, the peek() method is considered a "non-terminal" operation, meaning that it does not cause the stream to be evaluated or consumed. It is therefore free for the implementation to skip calls to peek() for optimization purposes. This can happen when the implementation determines that the results of the peek() operation are not needed for the subsequent terminal operation, or when the implementation can optimize the stream processing in a way that makes the peek() operation redundant.The Javadoc states that the main purpose of peek() method is to support debugging. Indeed, when you want to see the elements as they flow past a certain point in a pipeline, peek() is very useful.It is not necessarily related to debugging only, it can be used for a wide range of purposes, such as for debugging, logging, auditing, or for maintaining some form of state or context during the processing of a stream. However, as it is not guaranteed that peek() will be called for every element, it may not be suitable for these scenarios.Firebase Tools and Java 11


